retrieved_1: Dirleton Castle is a medieval fortress in the village of Dirleton, East Lothian, Scotland.
retrieved_2: It lies around 2 mi west of North Berwick, and around 19 mi east of Edinburgh.
retrieved_3: The oldest parts of the castle date to the 13th century, and it was abandoned by the end of the 17th century.
retrieved_4: Dirleton Kirk is situated to the north of the village green in Dirleton, in East Lothian, Scotland.
retrieved_5: Dirleton village lies on the south shore of the Firth of Forth 21 miles east of Edinburgh and two miles west of North Berwick on the A198 road.
retrieved_6: The church is at grid reference [ NT512842] .
retrieved_7: St. Mary's Priory, North Berwick, was a monastery of nuns in medieval East Lothian, Scotland.
retrieved_8: Founded by Donnchad I, Earl of Fife (owner of much of northern East Lothian) around 1150, the priory lasted for more than four centuries, declining and disappearing after the Scottish Reformation.
retrieved_9: It had been endowed by the Earls of Carrick as well as the Earls of Fife, but over time lost its dependence on these and came to be controlled by the more locally based Home (or Hume) family, who eventually acquired the priory's lands as a free barony.
retrieved_10: Lothian and Borders is an area in south-east Scotland consisting of the East Lothian, City of Edinburgh, Midlothian, West Lothian areas (collectively known as Lothian) along with the Scottish Borders.
retrieved_11: The Scottish Borders (Scots: "The Mairches" , "The Marches") is one of 32 council areas of Scotland.
retrieved_12: It borders the City of Edinburgh, Dumfries and Galloway, East Lothian, Midlothian, South Lanarkshire, West Lothian and, to the south and east, Northumberland in England.
retrieved_13: The administrative centre of the area is Newtown St Boswells.
gold_1: Yellowcraig, less commonly known as Broad Sands Bay, is a coastal area of forest, beach and grassland in East Lothian, south-east Scotland.

question: Who is the writer of this song that was inspired by words on a tombstone and was the first track on the box set Back to Mono?

retrieved_1: Back to Mono (1958–1969) is a box set (4 compact discs or 5 vinyl LPs) compilation of the recorded work of record producer Phil Spector, through the 1960s, released in 1991 by ABKCO as #7118-2.
retrieved_2: The first track, "To Know Him Is to Love Him," released in 1958, features Spector performing as part of the group the Teddy Bears.
retrieved_3: Initially a vinyl album-sized package, the box contained a booklet with photographs, complete song lyrics, discographical information, and a reproduction of the essay on Spector by Tom Wolfe, "The First Tycoon of Teen."
retrieved_4: The package also contained a small, round, red "Back to Mono" pin.
retrieved_5: Mono Masters is a compilation album by the Beatles, and is an alternate, all-mono version of the album "Past Masters".
retrieved_6: "Mono Masters" was originally a two-CD set included as part of "The Beatles in Mono" box set.
retrieved_7: The premise of this box set was to compile only Beatles material which was released or prepared for release with a dedicated mono mix (the set excludes later material mixed and released only in stereo, and material whose mono version was simply created as an equal mix of the two channels of the stereo version).
retrieved_8: As a result, the track listing for "Mono Masters" differs from "Past Masters" on the second half of disc two, omitting some later songs that never had a mono mix ("Old Brown Shoe", "The Ballad of John and Yoko" and "Let It Be"), and adding several songs released on stereo-only albums that had unreleased mono mixes.
retrieved_9: Tracks 9–12 and 15 were prepared in March 1969 for release as a 7" mono "Yellow Submarine" EP, two months after the release of the similarly titled soundtrack album, but the project was scrapped, although the EP was mastered.
retrieved_10: Subsequently, the tracks were only released in stereo (and in an electronically produced mono mixdown, or "fold-down", of the stereo mix), while the true mono mixes remained unreleased.
retrieved_11: "Get Back" (with B-side "Don't Let Me Down") was the final Beatles single mixed for mono format.
retrieved_12: It was released in the UK in mono, though the US release was in stereo.
retrieved_13: Thus, the songs that were originally released on stereo singles in the UK are omitted on this release.
retrieved_14: "To Know Him Is to Love Him" is a song written by Phil Spector, inspired by words on his father's tombstone, "To Know Him Was To Love Him."
retrieved_15: It was first recorded by the only vocal group of which he was a member, the Teddy Bears.
retrieved_16: Their recording spent three weeks at No. 1 on the "Billboard" Hot 100 singles chart in 1958, while reaching No. 2 on UK's "New Musical Express" chart.
retrieved_17: Peter & Gordon and Bobby Vinton later had hits with the song, with its title and lyrics changed to "To Know You Is to Love You".
retrieved_18: In 1987, the song was resurrected by Dolly Parton, Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris, whose "Trio" recording topped the U.S. country singles charts.
retrieved_20: Radiohead Box Set is a box set of the first six studio albums and one live album by the English rock band Radiohead, released on 10 December 2007.
retrieved_21: The box set is available as a seven CD box set, a digital download and a 4GB USB Stick.
retrieved_22: The box set peaked at #95 in Canada's album charts.
retrieved_23: Led Zeppelin Boxed Set 2 is a double album released by Atlantic Records on 21 September 1993.
retrieved_24: This box set features the rest of the English rock band Led Zeppelin's catalogue not included in the 1990 4-CD box set "Led Zeppelin", all digitally remastered, including the previously unreleased studio track "Baby Come On Home".
retrieved_25: A 54-page booklet was also included with the release.
retrieved_26: Between this box set and the 4-CD box set every track from the band's nine studio albums are featured along with two BBC live recordings; the band's only non-LP b-side; and one studio outtake.

gold_2: The first track, "To Know Him Is to Love Him," released in 1958, features Spector performing as part of the group the Teddy Bears.

retrieved_1: Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev, ( ; Russian: Михаи́л Серге́евич Горбачёв ; ] ; born 2 March 1931) is a former Soviet statesman.
retrieved_2: He was the eighth and last leader of the Soviet Union, having been General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union from 1985 until 1991.
retrieved_3: He was the country's head of state from 1988 until 1991 (titled as Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet from 1988 to 1989, as Chairman of the from 1989 to 1990, and as Soviet Union]] from 1990 to 1991).
retrieved_4: Andrei Pavlovich Kirilenko (Russian: Андре́й Па́влович Кириле́нко ; ] ; 8 September [O.S. 26 August] 1906 – 12 May 1990) was a Soviet statesman from the start to the end of the Cold War.
retrieved_5: In 1906, Kirilenko was born at Alexeyevka in Belgorod Oblast to a Ukrainian working-class family.
retrieved_6: He graduated in the 1920s from a local vocational school, and again in the mid-to-late 1930s from the Rybinsk Aviation Technology Institute.
retrieved_7: He became a member of the All-Union Communist Party (bolsheviks) in 1930.
retrieved_8: As many like him, Kirilenko climbed up the Soviet hierarchy through the "industrial ladder"; by the 1960s, he was Vice-Chairman of the Bureau of the Central Committee of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic (RSFSR).
retrieved_9: After Nikita Khrushchev's forced resignation, Kirilenko became Leonid Brezhnev's "chief lieutenant" within the Central Committee.
retrieved_10: Anastas Ivanovich Mikoyan ; 25 November 1895 – 21 October 1978) was an Old Bolshevik and Soviet statesman during the mandates of Lenin, Stalin, Khrushchev, and Brezhnev.
retrieved_11: He was the only Soviet politician who managed to remain at the highest levels of power within the Communist Party of the Soviet Union, as that power oscillated between the Central Committee and the Politburo, from the latter days of Lenin's rule, throughout the eras of Stalin and Khrushchev, until his peaceful retirement after the first months of Brezhnev's rule.
gold_1: The World Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates was initiated by Mikhail Gorbachev in the 90s, as a forum in which the Nobel Peace Laureates and the Peace Laureate Organizations could come together to address global issues with a view to encourage and support peace and human well being in the world.
gold_2: Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev, ( ; Russian: Михаи́л Серге́евич Горбачёв ; ] ; born 2 March 1931) is a former Soviet statesman.

question: Which British first-generation jet-powered medium bomber was used in the South West Pacific theatre of World War II?

subquery_2: Which British aircraft was English Electric Canberra? [ANSWER_2]
subanswer_2: English Electric Canberra is a British first-generation jet-powered medium bomber.
retrieved_1: The English Electric Canberra is a British first-generation jet-powered medium bomber that was manufactured during the 1950s.
retrieved_2: It was developed by English Electric during the mid-to-late 1940s in response to a 1944 Air Ministry requirement for a successor to the wartime de Havilland Mosquito fast-bomber.
retrieved_3: Amongst the performance requirements for the type was the demand for an outstanding high altitude bombing capability in addition to flying at high speeds.
retrieved_4: These were partly accomplished by making use of newly developed jet propulsion technology.
retrieved_5: When the Canberra was introduced to service with the Royal Air Force (RAF), the type's first operator, in May 1951, it became the service's first jet-powered bomber aircraft.
retrieved_6: The South West Pacific theatre, during World War II, was a major theatre of the war between the Allies and Japan.
retrieved_7: It included the Philippines, the Dutch East Indies (except for Sumatra), Borneo, Australia and its mandate Territory of New Guinea (including the Bismarck Archipelago) and the western part of the Solomon Islands.
retrieved_8: This area was defined by the Allied powers' South West Pacific Area (SWPA) command.
retrieved_9: No. 2 Squadron is a Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF) squadron that operates from RAAF Base Williamtown, near Newcastle, New South Wales.
retrieved_10: From its formation in 1916 as part of the Australian Flying Corps, it has flown a variety of aircraft types including fighters, bombers, and Airborne Early Warning & Control (AEW&C).
retrieved_11: During World War I, the squadron operated on the Western Front conducting fighter sweeps and ground-attack missions.
retrieved_12: It was disbanded in mid-1919, following the end of hostilities.
retrieved_13: The squadron was briefly re-raised in 1922 as part of the newly independent RAAF, but was disbanded after only a couple of months and not reformed until 1937.
retrieved_14: It saw action as a bomber unit in the South West Pacific theatre of World War II and, equipped with English Electric Canberra jets, in the Malayan Emergency and the Vietnam War.
retrieved_15: The squadron was again disbanded in 1982, following the retirement of the Canberra.
retrieved_16: It was re-formed in 2000 to operate the Boeing 737 AEW&C "Wedgetail".
retrieved_17: One of the six Boeing 737s was deployed to the Middle East in September 2014, as part of Australia's contribution to the military coalition against ISIS.
gold_1: It saw action as a bomber unit in the South West Pacific theatre of World War II and, equipped with English Electric Canberra jets, in the Malayan Emergency and the Vietnam War.
gold_2: The English Electric Canberra is a British first-generation jet-powered medium bomber that was manufactured during the 1950s.
